<h3 class="text-center my-4">Interesting Facts About Corals</h3>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">1. Coral Triangle Location</h4>
    <p>Tubbataha is part of the Coral Triangle, often called the "Amazon of the Seas," which supports 76% of the world's coral species.</p>
</section>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">2. Reef Size and Age</h4>
    <p>The reef covers 97,030 hectares and has formed over thousands of years, providing a unique glimpse into the evolution of marine ecosystems.</p>
</section>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">3. Global Significance</h4>
    <p>Tubbataha is one of the few pristine reef systems left in the world, offering a glimpse of marine ecosystems untouched by human activity.</p>
</section>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">4. Biodiversity Hub</h4>
    <p>Corals in Tubbataha support over 600 species of fish, sea turtles, sharks, and cetaceans, forming a critical part of the marine food web.</p>
</section>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">5. Resilience</h4>
    <p>Despite global threats like climate change, Tubbataha's remoteness and strict protection have helped it remain relatively healthy compared to other coral reefs.</p>
</section>

<h3 class="text-center my-4">Conservation Practices to Protect Corals</h3>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">1. Minimize Coral Damage While Diving</h4>
    <ul>
        <li>Do not touch or stand on corals.</li>
        <li>Ensure proper buoyancy to avoid accidental damage while snorkeling or diving.</li>
    </ul>
</section>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">2. Reduce Plastic Use</h4>
    <p>Plastics can suffocate or block sunlight essential for corals' photosynthesis. Use reusable alternatives to reduce pollution.</p>
</section>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">3. Limit Chemical Use</h4>
    <p>Avoid sunscreens with harmful chemicals like oxybenzone, which can bleach corals. Opt for reef-safe sunscreen to minimize harm.</p>
</section>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">4. Participate in Reef Monitoring and Cleanups</h4>
    <p>Volunteer for reef conservation programs or local clean-up drives to help keep Tubbataha Reef pristine.</p>
</section>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">5. Spread Awareness</h4>
    <p>Educate others about coral reef conservation and encourage sustainable practices to protect Tubbataha’s rich biodiversity.</p>
</section>

<h3 class="text-center my-4">Threats to Tubbataha's Corals</h3>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">1. Climate Change</h4>
    <p>Rising sea temperatures cause coral bleaching, weakening corals and disrupting marine ecosystems.</p>
</section>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">2. Illegal Fishing and Anchor Damage</h4>
    <p>Nets, dynamite fishing, and anchors can physically damage coral structures, causing long-term degradation.</p>
</section>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">3. Marine Pollution</h4>
    <p>Runoff from agricultural and industrial activities introduces toxins and sediments, which reduce water quality and suffocate corals.</p>
</section>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">4. Ocean Acidification</h4>
    <p>High carbon dioxide levels lower the pH of the ocean, weakening corals' ability to build skeletons and impacting reef health.</p>
</section>

